<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-11-20T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-11-20T02:00:00-05:00" n="255" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d255">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/453:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-11-20T15:00:00+08:00">November 20, 1929—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 21—2:55 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>1011. My 1008, November 15 [<hi rend="italic">19</hi>], 5 p.m. Following
                            from American Consul at Harbin: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“November 19, 3 p.m. Reports of serious Red aeroplane attacks on
                                    Chalainor, Tsagan and railway line, of which 30 kilometers
                                    destroyed between Chalainor and Hailar and at Mutanchiang,
                                    confirmed. On 17th passenger train fired upon, held up, and
                                    robbed near Tsagan by Red irregulars. Trains running as far as
                                        Horhonte<note n="11" xml:id="d255fn11">The same as
                                        Heierhungteh.</note>.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>